aa(lp288
VBruno Giussani: Thank you, Wendy.
p289
aVStay with me, because I have a question for you.
p290
aVYou mentioned different facilities.
p291
aVSo the Magellan Telescope is going up, but also ALMA and others in Chile
p292
aVand elsewhere, including in Hawaii.
p293
aVIs it about cooperation and complementarity, or about competition?
p294
aVI know there's competition in terms of funding, but what about the science?
p295
aa(lp296
VWendy Freedman: In terms of the science, they're very complementary.
p297
aVThe telescopes that are in space, the telescopes on the ground,
p298
aVtelescopes with different wavelength capability,
p299
aVtelescopes even that are similar, but different instruments \u2014
p300
aVthey will all look at different parts of the questions that we're asking.
p301
aVSo when we discover other planets, we'll be able to test those observations,
p302
aVwe'll be able to measure the atmospheres,
p303
aVbe able to look in space with very high resolution.
p304
aVSo, they're very complementary.
p305
aVYou're right about the funding, we compete;
p306
aVbut scientifically, it's very complementary.
p307
aa(lp308
VBG: Wendy, thank you very much for coming to TEDGlobal.
p309
aa(lp310
VWF: Thank you.
